        <h2>What every GC should prioritize in software</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Subcontractor management</strong> — Bid solicitation, PO issuance, and lien waiver tracking cut administrative time significantly</li>
          <li><strong>Budget vs. actual tracking</strong> — Know your job profitability in real time, not at closeout</li>
          <li><strong>Change order management</strong> — Every approved change should flow into your budget automatically</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule management</strong> — Gantt with dependencies that updates when delays occur</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile access</strong> — Your super needs to log daily reports from the site, not from the office</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Do I need different software for residential and commercial projects?</h3>
        <p>If you do both, yes — or you use a platform that covers the overlap well. Buildertrend works for light commercial (small office buildings, commercial tenant finish) but isn't built for complex commercial. Procore can handle residential but doesn't have the homeowner-facing features that residential GCs need. Most GCs who do both maintain separate platforms for each market segment.</p>

        <h3>What's the most important software feature for a GC?</h3>
        <p>Budget vs. actual tracking. Most construction company failures are caused by running jobs that are unprofitable without knowing it until the job is done. Software that gives you real-time cost visibility changes the game — you can see problems developing and take corrective action before they become losses.</p>

